## 8. Windows Task Scheduler Setup

Two jobs per biweekly cycle, with an ops window between them:

| Setting | Job 1 (Analysis) | Job 2 (Validate) |
|---|---|---|
| Task name | `WeCom-Audit-Phase1` | `WeCom-Audit-Phase2` |
| Trigger | Every 2 weeks, Thursday 08:00 | Every 2 weeks, Thursday 16:00 |
| Action | `pwsh -File Invoke-WeComAuditScheduler.ps1 -Phase Analysis -env PROD` | `pwsh -File Invoke-WeComAuditScheduler.ps1 -Phase Validate -env PROD` |
| Run as | Service account with NAS access | Same service account |

Both jobs must share the same biweekly trigger alignment (same start date). The scheduler auto-determines 2-week vs 4-week from the anchor — no need for separate 2-week/4-week jobs.

### Manual execution examples

```powershell
# Backfill a historical 4-week cycle
./Invoke-WeComAuditScheduler.ps1 -Phase Analysis -StartDate 20260319 -ForceCurrentRunWeeks 4 -env QA

# After ops copies files, validate the run
./Invoke-WeComAuditScheduler.ps1 -Phase Validate -env QA

# Or validate a specific run directly (bypass scheduler)
./Invoke-AuditValidate.ps1 -RunId 20260402_080000 -CurrentRunWeeks 2
```

